12
00:00:49.080 --> 00:00:54.280
We'll be using the game mode today to store information and so I think it'd be useful

13
00:00:54.360 --> 00:00:58.660
to cover what a game mode is and especially in relation to HMI.

14
00:00:58.660 --> 00:01:03.440
So the game mode first of all is singleton so it can be accessed by any class, meaning

15
00:01:03.440 --> 00:01:10.240
that whenever you have a session active, you can find the game mode based on any class

16
00:01:10.240 --> 00:01:13.560
that's currently in that scene.

17
00:01:13.560 --> 00:01:18.840
It holds data so you can easily access and store data inside the game mode.

18
00:01:18.840 --> 00:01:23.520
And the cool thing about this is that it only exists as long as the level is open.

19
00:01:23.520 --> 00:01:29.520
So we use the game instance and also save states for long term data storage.

20
00:01:29.520 --> 00:01:36.880
So if you just want to access information during the actual session, then you can have

21
00:01:36.880 --> 00:01:43.840
whatever variables or information you want to store inside the game mode and that will

22
00:01:43.840 --> 00:01:44.840
be fine.

23
00:01:44.840 --> 00:01:46.680
It's like a one shot use of data.

24
00:01:46.680 --> 00:01:52.000
If we're wanting to maybe change the color of a car and actually save that information,

25
00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:53.840
you wouldn't want to do that on the game mode.

26
00:01:53.840 --> 00:01:58.760
You'd want to do it either in the game instance or in a save state.

27
00:01:58.760 --> 00:02:01.560
So it's worth highlighting the differences there.

28
00:02:01.560 --> 00:02:07.300
When we talk about controller in this instance in HMI, we're talking about something that

29
00:02:07.300 --> 00:02:09.200
we can possess.

30
00:02:09.200 --> 00:02:15.120
So we will when we load the session and play the session, controller will become active

31
00:02:15.120 --> 00:02:19.240
and we can interact with this scene with our controller.

32
00:02:19.240 --> 00:02:23.160
So for our purposes today, our controller will be our camera manager.

33
00:02:23.160 --> 00:02:29.480
So it's a digital representation of a user and we possess it like a pawn in a scene.

34
00:02:29.480 --> 00:02:31.920
It can have input assigned to it.

35
00:02:31.920 --> 00:02:37.400
So we can bind either keyboard and mouse events or any other peripheral that you have plugged

36
00:02:37.400 --> 00:02:38.400
in.

37
00:02:38.400 --> 00:02:40.260
We can actually take input into the controller.

38
00:02:40.260 --> 00:02:44.480
So it allows for a lot of flexibility there as well.

39
00:02:44.720 --> 00:02:50.400
And as you can see in a HMI, the controller can be used to change the interaction modes

40
00:02:50.400 --> 00:02:52.520
and manage the information as well.

41
00:02:52.520 --> 00:02:59.080
So a lot of power in the controller and that is what we'll be using today to interact with

42
00:02:59.080 --> 00:03:00.080
that scene.

43
00:03:00.080 --> 00:03:07.600
A pawn on the other hand is a representation of generally your avatar in the world.

44
00:03:07.600 --> 00:03:10.920
So it's the user's visual or digital form.

45
00:03:11.360 --> 00:03:16.480
It's a CDO Singleton, but the HMI is like any visible pawn.

46
00:03:16.480 --> 00:03:22.280
So we just possess a camera to see the visual elements and there's no visual element needed

47
00:03:22.280 --> 00:03:26.080
because we don't need to move or manipulate anything.

48
00:03:26.080 --> 00:03:31.180
And then in a standard HMI game mode, the pawn class is set to none.

49
00:03:31.180 --> 00:03:37.960
So in that screen that we saw here, when we have a pawn class, we won't need any kind

50
00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:44.400
of pawn class assigned because the controller will be handling everything in this instance.

